One evening, I set out 200 miles north through the back roads of New Hampshire to find wild lupines.  There  are fields with thousands of them.  All different sizes, between 10inches to 4ft tall. I parked my truck on the dirt road and carefully admired these beautiful flowers.  They remind me of something not of this world. It was a peaceful evening of crickets chirping and the sound of flowing water from a nearby creek. 

Here are my favorite frames. Shot with my Slik tripod and Sony A7R4 and 14mm GM

There is something special about early summer sunsets. The smell of flowers and saltwater ocean. While capturing my composition, I laid still, taking in the sun and the waves, and witnessed the celebration of a nearby fisherman who caught a huge fish. ⛺️🦈 ☀️
Coastal wild flowers at sunset.
Alien worlds of the flora kind.  Lupines reaching for the nighttime sky.

I’ve wanted to visit this majestic place for awhile, I made the stop after visiting family in western New York. The scale of this gorge was amazing and so peaceful. As I was searching for my composition, others started watching me as I set up, and wanted to take silky smooth water shots. They didn’t have a camera so I held mini photo lessons on teaching how to capture long exposure waterfalls with their smartphone. I love to teach and watching them capture the falls with creativity and wonder, made my day.

I drove 5hrs for this shot, out to the tip of Cape Cod. The rising moon to my east created amazing contrast to the footsteps in the sand. Down beach people were enjoying a beautiful night around a fire. I laid here for 2hrs as this small geomagnetic storm came through.  It’s important to note, I could not see this with my naked eye. This was a long exposure. I used my Aurora App, to notify me.

Last night’s Geminid meteor shower was amazing. Large bright fireballs in the sky, up to 120 per hour. Rhode Island’s clear night sky was the perfect backdrop for it. This photo features our winter Milky Way view, specifically the Orion Nebula complex.  It’s not smiling at you, that is Banard’s  Loop. This was shot in Ha-RGB. H-alpha is a specific deep-red visible spectral line with a wavelength of 656nm. Many nebulae in the night sky emit a strong signal of light in this wavelength and a hydrogen-alpha filter helps to isolate and record this signal with my camera. 

📷: SonyA7r4, 14mm GM f1.8
Tracking: Star Adventurer GTI

Pleiades - M45. On a cold winter night, I pointed my camera to one of my favorite star clusters.  The stars in the Pleiades were all born around the same time from a gigantic cloud of gas and dust. The brightest stars in the formation glow a luminous hot blue. It was a pleasure to finally meet @theeyeofthemind . James and I sat there amazed, talking about how clear the Rhode Island skies were on this night. 

📸: SonyA7R4 unmodified.
